column2: Using externally controlled strings in a command line may allow a malicious user to change the meaning of the command.
Prepending a backslash to an ordinary character in a string does not have any effect, and may make regular expressions constructed from this string behave unexpectedly.
column4: The escape sequence '\.' is equivalent to just '.', so the sequence may still represent a meta-character when it is used in a [["regular expression"|"relative:///repo.js:83:31:83:50"]].
